class='post-entry post-entry-type-standard post-entry-2507 with_slideshow'> <span
class='entry-border-overflow extralight-border'></span><div
class='slideshow_container  seven units alpha offset-by-one'><ul
class='preloading slideshow fade_slider' data-autorotation='false' data-autorotation-timer='5' ><li
data-animation='random'  class='featured featured_container1 caption_left caption_left_framed caption_framed' ><a
href='http://rottmann.net/2013/01/an-iphone-lovers-confession-i-switched-to-the-nexus-4-completely/'><img
src='http://cdn.rottmann.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/nexus4.jpg?f329b7' title='nexus4' alt='' data-imgh='415' data-imgw='765' /></a></li></ul></div><h1 class='post-title offset-by-one '> <a
href="http://rottmann.net/2013/01/an-iphone-lovers-confession-i-switched-to-the-nexus-4-completely/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link: An iPhone lover&#8217;s confession: I switched to the Nexus 4. Completely.">An iPhone lover&#8217;s confession: I switched to the Nexus 4. Completely. <span
class='post-format-icon minor-meta'></span> </a></h1><div
class="one unit alpha blog-meta"><div
class='side-container side-container-date'><div
class='side-container-inner'> <span
class='date-day'>03</span> <span
class='date-month'>Jan</span></div></div></div><div
class="seven units entry-content"> <span
class='date-container minor-meta meta-color'>03/01/2013</span><div
class="avia-box normal   light-gray rounded shadow "><span
class="avia-innerbox" > Update: Shortly after publishing this article here, it became <a
href="http://d.ralf.me/EuAS" target="_blank">#1 on Y Combinator&#8217;s Hacker News</a>, republished by <a
href="http://gizmodo.com/5973073/an-iphone-lovers-confession-i-switched-to-the-nexus-4-completely" target="_blank">GIZMODO</a>, picked up by <a
href="http://readwrite.com/2013/01/04/android-now-outshines-ios-in-almost-every-aspect" target="_blank">ReadWriteWeb&#8217;s Editor-in-Chief (Dan Lyons)</a>, commented on by <a
href="http://news.cnet.com/8301-13579_3-57563527-37/android-challenges-the-iphone-in-every-category/" target="_blank">CNET News</a>, <a
href="http://gigaom.com/2013/01/15/why-im-thinking-of-ditching-my-precious-iphone-for-an-android/" target="_blank">GigaOM&#8217;s Mathew Ingram</a> and the <a
href="http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/421651/20130108/nexus-4-why-pick-google-lg-smartphone.htm" target="_blank">International Business Times</a>. I also <a
href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FnC-Zo62a_c&amp;feature=plcp" target="_blank">gave a lengthy interview in German</a> regarding the topic, which go subsequently <a
href="http://www.theeuropean.de/gunnar-sohn/5740-iphone-verliert-gegen-android" target="_blank">covered in The European</a> (German only).</p><p>The discussion mainly takes place <a
href="https://plus.google.com/u/0/106658337982640166595/posts/W53DStqru8V" target="_blank">over on Google+</a>.<br
/> </span></div><div
class="spacer8"></div><p>First things first, I&#8217;d love to get in touch on <a
href="https://plus.google.com/106658337982640166595/posts" target="_blank">Google+</a> and <a
href="http://twitter.com/ralf" target="_blank">Twitter (@ralf)</a>.</p><p><strong>Over the past few years I&#8217;ve invested a lot into Apple products and services.</strong></p><p><img
class="alignright size-medium wp-image-2513" alt="My Nexus 4" src="http://cdn.rottmann.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/n4-google-now-169x300.png?f329b7" width="169" height="300" />If you&#8217;d come by my house, you&#8217;d find four of the latest Apple TVs, two iMacs, the latest MacBook Air, a MacBook Pro, more than five AirPort Express stations and Apple&#8217;s Time Capsule. You could touch every single iPhone, from the first up to the iPhone 5, iPads ranging from first generation to fourth and we&#8217;ve lately added two iPad minis.</p><p>My iTunes Library comprises well over 8.000 songs – all purchased via the iTunes Store. No matter whom you would ask, everybody will confirm that I&#8217;m what some folks call an Apple fanboy.</p><p>The reach of Apple&#8217;s products goes beyond my personal life.</p><p>As the co-founder of <a
href="http://www.grandcentrix.net" target="_blank">Germany&#8217;s largest mobile development shop</a>, I&#8217;m dealing with apps – predominantly iOS powered – in my daily professional life.</p><p>Driven primarily by the business I run, I tried to give Android a chance more than once.</p><p>In various self-experiments, I tried to leave my iPhone at home for the Motorola Droid, the Nexus One, the Samsung Galaxy S II and S III – and always switched straight back to the iPhone. None of those Android devices have worked for me – yet.</p><p><strong>And then I got the Nexus 4.</strong></p><p>When the latest Google flagship Android device shipped, I almost <em>expected</em> it to turn out as yet another &#8220;take-a-look-and-sell-it-on-ebay&#8221; experience. <em>Little did I know.</em></p><p>It&#8217;s now almost two weeks since I switched the Nexus 4 on for the first time – and meanwhile I completely moved to it, leaving my iPhone 5 at home. Do I miss anything? Nope. Except iMessage. More to that later.</p><p>In this somewhat lengthy post, I&#8217;ll try to explain why.</p><p> <a
href="http://rottmann.net/2013/01/an-iphone-lovers-confession-i-switched-to-the-nexus-4-completely/" class="more-link">Read more  &rarr;</a><div
